'''Albright’s hereditary osteodystrophy''' is form of [[osteodystrophy]],<ref name="Bolognia">{{cite book |author=Rapini, Ronald P.; Bolognia, Jean L.; Jorizzo, Joseph L. |title=Dermatology: 2-Volume Set |publisher=Mosby |location=St. Louis |year=2007 |pages=657 |isbn=1-4160-2999-0 }}</ref> otherwise known as [[Pseudohypoparathyroidism]] type 1a.

==Characteristics==
The disorder is characterized by a lack of responsiveness to [[parathyroid hormone]],<ref name="pmid9506735">{{cite journal |author=Namnoum AB, Merriam GR, Moses AM, Levine MA |title=Reproductive dysfunction in women with Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy |journal=J. Clin. Endocrinol. Metab. |volume=83 |issue=3 |pages=824–9 |year=1998 |month=March |pmid=9506735 |doi= 10.1210/jc.83.3.824|url=http://jcem.endojournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=9506735}}</ref> resulting in low serum calcium, high serum phosphate, and appropriately high serum parathyroid hormone.  

Individuals with Albright’s hereditary osteodystrophy have [[short stature]], characteristically shortened fourth and fifth [[metacarpal]]s, rounded [[Facies (medical)|facies]], and often mild mental retardation.<ref>{{OMIM|103580}}</ref><ref name="pmid16116826">{{cite journal |author=Garavelli L, Pedori S, Zanacca C, ''et al.'' |title=Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy (pseudohypoparathyroidism type Ia): clinical case with a novel mutation of GNAS1 |journal=Acta Biomed |volume=76 |issue=1 |pages=45–8 |year=2005 |month=April |pmid=16116826 }}</ref>

Albright’s hereditary osteodystrophy is commonly known as Pseudohypoparathyroidism because the kidney responds as if parathyroid hormone were absent. In fact, blood levels of parathyroid hormone are elevated in Pseudohypoparathyroidism due to the continued Hyperphosphatemia & Hypocalcemia.

==Genetics==
[[Image:Autosomal dominant - en.svg|thumb|right|Albright&#39;s hereditary osteodystrophy has an autosomal dominant maternal pattern of [[heredity|inheritance]].<!-- (Someone please change this image, it is not accurate. The pattern of inheritance is maternal <http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/omim/103580>, whereas paternal inheritance of loss of function mutation results in pseudopseudohypoparathyroidism
<http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/omim/612463> -->]]

It is associated with [[epigenetic]] [[genetic imprinting]].<ref name="pmid17405843">{{cite journal |author=de Nanclares GP, Fernández-Rebollo E, Santin I, ''et al.'' |title=Epigenetic defects of GNAS in patients with pseudohypoparathyroidism and mild features of Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy |journal=J. Clin. Endocrinol. Metab. |volume=92 |issue=6 |pages=2370–3 |year=2007 |month=June |pmid=17405843 |doi=10.1210/jc.2006-2287 |url=http://jcem.endojournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=17405843}}</ref> Because of this the disease can occur when a mother with mild clinical symptoms or a de novo mutation of the maternal allele passes it to her offspring. 

It is believed to be inherited in an [[autosomal]] [[Dominance (genetics)|dominant]] pattern.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=6278930 |year=1982 |month=January |author=Fitch N |title=Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy: a review |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=11–29 |doi=10.1002/ajmg.1320110104 |journal=American journal of medical genetics |url=http://toxnet.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/sis/search/r?dbs+hsdb:@term+@na+CALCIUM+COMPOUNDS |format=Free full text |last2=Opitz |first2=John M. |last3=Herrmann |first3=JüRgen}}</ref>

It is associated with a [[Gs alpha subunit]] deficiency.<ref name="pmid2109828">{{cite journal |author=Patten JL, Johns DR, Valle D, ''et al.'' |title=Mutation in the gene encoding the stimulatory G protein of adenylate cyclase in Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=322 |issue=20 |pages=1412–9 |year=1990 |month=May |pmid=2109828 |doi= 10.1056/NEJM199005173222002}}</ref>

==Eponym==
The disorder bears the name of [[Fuller Albright]], who characterized it in 1942.<ref name="pmid7837255">{{cite journal |author=Wilson LC, Trembath RC |title=Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy |journal=J. Med. Genet. |volume=31 |issue=10 |pages=779–84 |year=1994 |month=October |pmid=7837255 |pmc=1050125 |doi= 10.1136/jmg.31.10.779|url=http://jmg.bmj.com/content/31/10/779.long | format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Albright F, Burnett CH, Smith PH, ''et al.'' |title=Pseudo-hypoparathyroidism-example of 'Seabright-Bantam syndrome'; report of three cases |journal=Endocrinology |volume=30 |pages=922–932 |year=1942}}</ref> He was also responsible for characterizing [[McCune-Albright syndrome]] as well as a number of other bone disorders.

He originally named it "Sebright Bantam syndrome", after the [[Sebright (chicken)|Sebright Bantam]], which demonstrated an analogous hormone insensitivity.<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|164}}</ref>

Much less commonly, the term "Martin-Albright syndrome" is used,<ref name="pmid19138295">{{cite journal |author=Quist SR, Franke I, Hiort O, Gollnick HP, Leverkus M |title=First diagnosis of Martin-Albright syndrome in a 58-year-old patient |journal=J Dtsch Dermatol Ges |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=43–5 |year=2009 |month=January |pmid=19138295 |doi=10.1111/j.1610-0387.2008.06862.x}}</ref> after the first author of a 1940 paper in a Swiss medical journal that may have described a case.<ref>{{WhoNamedIt|synd|1654}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Martin D, Bourdillon J |title=Un cas de tétanie idiopathique chronique. Échec thérapeutique de la graffe d’un adénome parathyroïdien |journal=Revue médicale de la Suisse romande |volume=60 |pages=1166–77 |year=1940 |location=Lausanne}}</ref>

